1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,965
What is a text file?

2
00:00:01,965 --> 00:00:06,910
Text files are files with text in them that use a specific character-set,

3
00:00:06,910 --> 00:00:11,280
contain no rules for structure and no formatting like italics or bowling,

4
00:00:11,280 --> 00:00:13,995
have no media like images or video,

5
00:00:13,995 --> 00:00:16,470
and have lines of texts that are separated by

6
00:00:16,470 --> 00:00:19,530
newline characters or backslash ends in Python.

7
00:00:19,530 --> 00:00:24,150
Now, these characters are typically invisible in most software applications,

8
00:00:24,150 --> 00:00:28,080
and it can be viewed and edited in simple text editors.

9
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:29,900
As we've talked about before,

10
00:00:29,900 --> 00:00:33,530
flat files can be text files that have a specific tabular structure.

11
00:00:33,530 --> 00:00:35,900
Whereas text files that fall out of

12
00:00:35,900 --> 00:00:39,740
the flat file category can be either structured or unstructured.

13
00:00:39,740 --> 00:00:43,265
Let's take a look at an example of a very popular corpus or

14
00:00:43,265 --> 00:00:46,790
a collection of texts made up of individual text files.

15
00:00:46,790 --> 00:00:48,425
The 20 newsgroup data,

16
00:00:48,425 --> 00:00:52,355
which has about 20,000 documents partitioned across 20 newsgroups,

17
00:00:52,355 --> 00:00:56,950
including topics like space or Mideast politics or computer graphics.

18
00:00:56,950 --> 00:01:01,550
Here we have an example of the.TXT file for the computer graphics newsgroup,

19
00:01:01,550 --> 00:01:04,580
which has about 975 messages in it.

20
00:01:04,580 --> 00:01:06,395
Assuming this data is cleaned,

21
00:01:06,395 --> 00:01:09,745
one cool thing that we can do is create a word cloud.

22
00:01:09,745 --> 00:01:11,345
Take a look at this word cloud,

23
00:01:11,345 --> 00:01:14,660
which is serving as a visual representation of the texts in our data-set.

24
00:01:14,660 --> 00:01:17,510
A word cloud is showing us how frequently words are occurring

25
00:01:17,510 --> 00:01:20,380
within the text by displaying them in different font sizes.

26
00:01:20,380 --> 00:01:24,050
For example in a subset of the comp graphics newsgroup data-set,

27
00:01:24,050 --> 00:01:28,475
we can see that the words graphics and subject are two very popular words.

28
00:01:28,475 --> 00:01:30,920
This gives us an immediate understanding of

29
00:01:30,920 --> 00:01:34,290
the dominant themes present in the text data-set.

